Beijing University of Posts and Telecommunications

Multi-task learning (MTL) seeks to learn a single model
Layer 1, 4, and 8 of ResNet18 (from left to right)
to accomplish multiple tasks by leveraging shared information among the tasks. Existing MTL models, however,
have been known to suffer from negative interference among
tasks. Efforts to mitigate task interference have focused on
either loss/gradient balancing or implicit parameter partitioning with partial overlaps among the tasks.
paper, we propose ETR-NLP to mitigate task interference
through a synergistic combination of non-learnable primitives (NLPs) and explicit task routing ().

From a layer design perspective, we propose using nonlearnable primitives (NLPs) to extract task-agnostic features and allow each task to choose optimal combinations of these features adaptively. There is growing evidence that features extracted from NLPs can be very effective for single-task settings, including for image classification [

In this paper, we present the Explicit Task Routing with
Non-Learnable Primitives (ETR-NLP) module for multitask learning.
The ETR-NLP module introduces nonlearnable primitives for extracting task-agnostic and diverse
features and explicit task routing to extract task-specific
features for each task. Both non-learnable primitives and
explicit task routing can provide the flexibility needed to

A. An Extended Description of Related Work
Existing methods related to MTL architectures can be
classified into encoder or decoder-focused ones. Encoderfocused approaches primarily lay emphasis on architectures that can encode multi-purpose feature representations
through supervision from multiple tasks. Such encoding is
typically achieved, for example, via feature fusion [
start from the feature representations learned at the encoding stage, and further refine them at the decoding stage
by distilling information across tasks in a one-off [
] manner. Due to inherent layer sharing, the approaches above
typically suffer from task interference and negative transfer [
